<RE>
MINNESOTA (MN)
NORTH AMERICA (NME)
NEW YORK (NY)
UNITED STATES (US)
</RE>
<LP>
   Minnesota Mining &amp; Manufacturing Co. said its researchers
have developed the first blue-green laser diode, calling it a
"major breakthrough in laser technology."
   The prototype device has the potential to triple or
quadruple the amount of data that can be stored on optical
and compact discs, the St. Paul, Minn., company said. It also
"opens new opportunities" for laser applications in fields
such as imaging, printing and communications.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   But 3M cautioned that "we're targeting two years" to
resolve technical hurdles before the so-called semiconductor
diode could become commercially viable.
   Semiconductor diodes, the size of a grain of sand or
smaller, convert electrical signals into tiny laser beams.
While best known for their use in recording and playing
compact discs, the inexpensive laser-producing chips are also
used in a host of other communication devices. But the chips
currently produce light only at the infrared -- or sometimes
visible red -- end of the spectrum.
   The laser diode developed by 3M produces "the shortest
wavelength ever generated by a semiconductor laser diode,"
the scientists said. The smaller the laser beam's wavelength,
the more densely it can pack optical data into an
informationstorage device.
   The 3M scientists' work is to be published shortly in the
science journal Applied Physics Letters.
   The 3M researchers used a new combination of materials to
construct the laser diode. While the chip's surface still
rests on a conventional base of gallium arsenide, the company
said its scientists were the first to successfully make use
of zinc selenide.
   For decades, the scientists wrote, zinc selenide has been
"promising" for development of a diode laser that could
produce visible light, but difficulties in "doping" the
compounds -- chemically treating them to make them effective
as semiconductors -- had previously blocked use of the
unconventional combination. Recent technological developments
both in doping and alternative treatments have lowered the
barriers, the scientists said.
   Other companies, both in the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION>, are hard at
work on diodes that produce visible light. Scientists at
<ORGANIZATION>International Business Machines Corp.</ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION>Almaden Research
Center</ORGANIZATION> last year created a "potentially practical source of
blue laser light," by passing an infrared laser beam from a
conventional diode through a special crystal. The crystal
effectively halves the resulting beam's wavelength, bringing
it into the visible spectrum.
   <ORGANIZATION>IBM</ORGANIZATION>'s experimental blue-laser device currently converts
electricity into light at about <PERCENT>10%</PERCENT> efficiency; 3M said its
prototype is about <PERCENT>20%</PERCENT> to <PERCENT>25%</PERCENT> efficient.
   <PERSON>Charles Walker</PERSON>, head of 3M's <ORGANIZATION>Photonics Research Lab</ORGANIZATION>, said
the researchers are "absolutely thrilled" with the device.
But he said "We have to . . . take it from something that
operates in a pulsed mode at low power at room temperature,
to something that operates in the continuous mode at room
temperature." The device currently operates continuously only
at extremely low temperatures.
</TEXT>
