<LEADPARA>  Scientists at AT&amp;T's Bell Laboratories announced Thursday that they had
produced the world's smallest lasers, an advance that one day may simplify the
manufacture of a new generation of ultrafast computers controlled by beams of
light.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Business  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  TINY LASERS MAY SPEED UP COMPUTERS  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     The same technology may also have other promising applications, including
building sensitive artificial-vision systems that could operate in a manner
similar to the human retina, researchers said.;   The <ORGANIZATION>Bell Labs</ORGANIZATION> research team
presented its work <DATE>Thursday</DATE> in <LOCATION>San Jose</LOCATION> at the annual meeting of the <ORGANIZATION>Optical
Society of America.</ORGANIZATION>;   Part of the report's significance is that the new
lasers -- which look like microscopic thumbtacks whose round tops emit
piercing beams of light -- can be made in arrays by the same process that is
used to make modern semiconductors.;   Thus the researchers said they believed
that optical computers, which exist today only in theory, might some day be
able to follow the same falling cost curves that have been emblematic of the
microelectronics industry.;   "We're hoping that when you get to computing
speeds above a billion cycles per second that optics will play a major part,"
said <PERSON>Richart Slusher</PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION>Bell Labs Optical Physics Research
Department</ORGANIZATION>. "The key is whether these technologies will be cost effective.";  
The new lasers are made by alternating one or more layers of indium gallium
arsenide with layers of indium gallium arsenide phosphide. The thin layers
that constitute the laser head are only 400 atoms thick. The researchers then
etch away some material to leave the tiny thumbtack-shaped structures that can
emit laser light in several directions.;   So far, prototypes of tiny lasers
that are 2, 5 and 10 microns in diameter have been manufactured using the new
process. By comparison, a human hair is approximately 75 microns in diameter
and a conventional laser beam used to play a compact disk player is 250
microns in diameter.;   The new semiconductor laser was designed by <PERSON>Sam
McCall</PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION>Bell Labs</ORGANIZATION> physicist.;   The researchers said that they would now
attempt a second key technological step: designing photon "wires" to guide the
beams emitted by the lasers.;   By building circuits of optical lasers and
other components, the researchers said they hoped to be able to fabricate
systems that would permit computer designers to create reliable connections
between computer chips in high-speed systems.;   The new lasers operate at
extremely low power levels and therefore would be well-suited as light sources
for future optical switches, the researchers said.  </TEXT>
