<LP>
   Toshiba Corp. announced that researchers at its Toshiba
R&amp;D Center have developed a prototype red-light semiconductor
laser, or laser diode, with the highest optical output power
of any continuous-wave visible laser diode in the world.
   The new prototype device is expected to be used as a new
light source for optical information storage products,
replacing conventional semiconductor lasers, Toshiba said in
Tokyo.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The new device emits a laser with a maximum optical output
power of 106 milliwatts, or mW, at a wavelength of 690
nanometers, or nm. Conventional devices, used as light
sources to read and write data for storage products such as
electronic document filing systems and CD-ROMs, emit an
invisible laser beam with 30mW of output power and an 830nm
wavelength.
   <ORGANIZATION>Toshiba</ORGANIZATION> said demand is increasing for devices with higher
output power and a shorter wavelength in order to store data
at a higher density and read the data more accurately. The
higher the density becomes, the more power is required for
writing and reading data.
</TEXT>
