<HL>
   Technology:
   AT&amp;T's Bell Labs
   Develops a Laser
   For Use in Chips
   ----
   By John J. Keller
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
11/08/91
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B8
</SO>
<CO>
   T
</CO>
<MS>
TECHNOLOGY (TEC)
UTILITIES (UTI)
</MS>
<IN>
COMMUNICATIONS TECHNOLOGY (CMT)
COMPUTERS AND INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY (CPR)
SEMICONDUCTORS, INTEGRATED CHIPS (SEM)
TELEPHONE SYSTEMS, INCLUDING CELLULAR (TLS)
</IN>
<NS>
NEW PRODUCTS &amp; SERVICES (PDT)
SCIENCE &amp; TECHNOLOGY (SCN)
</NS>
<RE>
NEW JERSEY (NJ)
NORTH AMERICA (NME)
NEW YORK (NY)
UNITED STATES (US)
</RE>
<LP>
   Scientists at American Telephone &amp; Telegraph Co.'s Bell
Laboratories said they have developed the world's smallest
semiconductor lasers.
   AT&amp;T said the lasers are so tiny (about five microns in
diameter) that at least 10,000 would fit on the head of a
pin. AT&amp;T and its rivals have been racing to boost
transmission power of fiber-optic communications equipment
and to miniaturize devices that comprise such gear to reduce
cost and make them easier to service.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   "This is a very novel semiconductor laser structure," said
<PERSON>Erich Ippen</PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION>Massachusetts Institute of Technology</ORGANIZATION>
professor who specializes in lasers and optics. "The use of
high-density microscopic lasers as interconnects is
potentially quite important" for linking information systems
in the future, he said.
   <ORGANIZATION>AT&amp;T</ORGANIZATION> is looking at using "these beautiful little
structures" as communications devices for optical switches
and connectors for linking computers and the devices within
them, said <PERSON>Richart Slusher</PERSON>, chief of <ORGANIZATION>Bell Labs' Optical
Physics Research</ORGANIZATION> department, <LOCATION>Murray Hill</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>N.J.</LOCATION> However, <ORGANIZATION>AT&amp;T</ORGANIZATION>
scientists must first show that the new devices can be made
as inexpensively as current electrical connectors and that
they are compatible with silicon-based electronic equipment,
he added.
   Pictures supplied by <ORGANIZATION>AT&amp;T</ORGANIZATION> show the microscopic devices,
dubbed "microdisk lasers," look like thumbtacks when viewed
through a scanning electron microscope. The head of each one
of these "tacks" is 400 atoms thick, or one-thousandth the
diameter of a human hair. <PERSON>Dr. Slusher</PERSON> said the devices are
<ORGANIZATION>Bell Labs</ORGANIZATION>' "biggest breakthrough" since so-called
surface-emitting lasers were developed about three years ago.
Such lasers use two microscopic mirrors to concentrate a
light beam on the laser chip's interior surface before
shooting the beam in the form of a cone.
   The new lasers were designed by <ORGANIZATION>Bell Labs</ORGANIZATION>' researcher <PERSON>Sam
McCall</PERSON> to operate in the so-called "whispering gallery" mode,
named for the sound effect associated with <ORGANIZATION>St. Paul's
Cathedral</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>London</LOCATION>, where a person can whisper and be heard
clearly along the wall of the dome. In a similar fashion, <PERSON>Dr.
McCall</PERSON>'s lasers are said to shoot their light pulses or
photons along the edge of the disk-shaped laser, or the path
of least resistance, <ORGANIZATION>AT&amp;T</ORGANIZATION> said.
   Each laser, which is crafted of indium gallium arsenide
"sandwiched" between indium gallium arsenide phosphide, took
about nine months to develop, said <PERSON>Dr. Slusher</PERSON>, who noted
that <PERSON>Dr. McCall</PERSON> worked on the team that developed <ORGANIZATION>AT&amp;T</ORGANIZATION>'s
surface-emitting devices.
</TEXT>
