<HEAD>Blue Laser Could Mean Big Gains in Data Storage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GAINESVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A zinc selenide laser that produces a
blue beam and can be focused more tightly than other lasers could
eventually triple the amount of information stored on optical
computer disks, its developer says.
   Japanese researchers in <DATE>March</DATE> developed a zinc selenide laser,
but it had to be cooled to 135 degrees below zero Fahrenheit,
according to the <ORGANIZATION>University of Florida</ORGANIZATION>, which announced a more
practical, room-temperature laser.
   Zinc selenide produces a blue beam that can focus on a spot
one-third the size of that produced by current materials, packing
information more densely on optical disks, increasing capacity.
Optical storage has been slow to be adopted in computers because it
is not as economical as magnetic storage.
   But optical disks have some marked advantages, primarily in
volume. The NeXT computer developed by <ORGANIZATION>Apple</ORGANIZATION> founder <PERSON>Steven Jobs</PERSON> is
the first desktop model to use an optical disk as a primary storage
device.
   <PERSON>Peter Zory</PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION>University of Florida</ORGANIZATION> electrical engineer who led
the development of the zinc selenide laser, said that before it
makes its way into use for information storage, it will be
necessary to develop a blue laser diode of the same material.
Diodes allow lasers to be powered by electricity. Without them,
semiconductor lasers must be powered by other lasers or electron
beams.
   Zory, who has worked on lasers for <ORGANIZATION>IBM</ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION>General Electric</ORGANIZATION>,
said <ORGANIZATION>IBM</ORGANIZATION> is trying another technique called second harmonic
generation. ``It's expensive but they're doing it anyway, because
they want that blue light. If we come in soon with the blue diode,
it will blow that technology out of the water.''
   <PERSON>Glenn Sincerbox</PERSON>, a former colleague of Zory's who manages
optical recording for <ORGANIZATION>IBM</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>San Jose</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Calif.</LOCATION>, said, ``Blue lasers
are very important. We consider them strategic.''
</TEXT>
